id: npm-publish-shape
title: npm package shape for public publish
scope: feature
owners: [@jana]
paths: [package.json]
surfaces: [npm publish]
dependencies: [cli-skeleton, mcp-skeleton]

intent:
  Governs the npm-publishable shape of the `typed-nl` package: which
  fields `package.json` MUST carry, which files get bundled into the
  tarball, and which get excluded. The package ships three bins —
  `typed-nl` (primary; enables `npx typed-nl <cmd>` since npx defaults
  to a bin matching the package name), `tnl` (short alias pointing at
  the same CLI entry; preferred global command), and `tnl-mcp-server`
  (MCP server entry, used via `npx -p typed-nl tnl-mcp-server`). This
  TNL is the contract between the repo state and what adopters get
  from `npm install`.

behaviors:
  - `package.json` MUST have `"private"` unset or `false` — the package is publishable.
  - `package.json` MUST declare the following fields with non-empty values: `name`, `version`, `description`, `type`, `bin`, `engines.node`, `license`, `repository`, `homepage`, `bugs`, `keywords`, `author`.
  - `package.json` MUST NOT declare `"publishConfig": { "access": "..." }`. The package is unscoped (`typed-nl`), which publishes public by default; an explicit `publishConfig.access` is noise.
  - `package.json` MUST declare a `"files"` allowlist that includes exactly: `dist/`, `LICENSE`, `README.md`. The allowlist MUST NOT include `src/`, `tests/`, `tnl/`, `internal_docs/`, `node_modules/`, `behavioral-tests/`, `evals/`, or tarball-polluting root files. `package.json` itself is always included by npm regardless of the allowlist.
  - The repo MUST NOT contain a `.npmignore` file at the root — the `files` allowlist is the single source of truth for what ships. If both exist npm uses `.npmignore`, which is error-prone; an allowlist makes the shipped contents auditable from `package.json` alone.
  - The `repository` field MUST be an object with `type: "git"` and `url` pointing to the public GitHub repo (`https://github.com/janaraj/tnl.git`).
  - `keywords` MUST include at least: `tnl`, `typed-natural-language`, `agent`, `claude-code`, `mcp`, `contracts`. These are the terms adopters search npm for.
  - The version MUST follow semver; the first public release MUST be `0.1.0` (preview — public but pre-1.0 API stability). Prior `0.0.1` is the unpublished scaffolding version.
  - `license` MUST be `"MIT"`, matching the repo root `LICENSE` file. The `LICENSE` file MUST continue to be present at the repo root (npm includes it automatically, and the `files` allowlist also names it explicitly).
  - Tests MUST cover: `package.json` is valid JSON and parses; all MUST-required fields are present and non-empty; `files` allowlist is exactly `['dist/', 'LICENSE', 'README.md']`; `publishConfig` is absent (unscoped package, no override needed); `private` is absent or `false`; no `.npmignore` exists at the repo root; `keywords` array contains each of the required terms; `license` is `"MIT"`; `repository.url` points at the `janaraj/tnl` GitHub repo; `version` starts with `0.1.0`.

non-goals:
  - CI-driven publish automation (`workflow_dispatch` release job) — deferred.
  - Signed commits / provenance via `--provenance` — strong candidate for a follow-up TNL once first publish stabilizes.
  - Multi-tag release channels (`latest`, `next`, `canary`) — first publish uses default `latest`.
  - Changelog generation — a plain `CHANGELOG.md` is a SHOULD, not a MUST; format is author-chosen.
  - Dual CJS/ESM publish — package is ESM-only (matches `"type": "module"` and existing build config).
  - Minimum Node version bump below current floor (Node 20). Raising it later is fine; lowering is out of scope.
  - Automated `npm publish` from tests — publishing is a user-driven step. Tests verify shape, not execution.
  - npm account creation / auth / 2FA setup — one-time manual steps on npmjs.com, not files the TNL can enforce.

rationale:
  Why `files` allowlist, not `.npmignore`: deny-lists are easy to
  forget. Every new top-level directory requires remembering to add
  it to `.npmignore`; an allowlist defaults to "excluded unless
  named," which is safer. Also makes `package.json` self-documenting
  for what ships.

  Why first version is `0.1.0`, not `1.0.0`: API stability isn't
  committed yet. `0.x.y` signals "usable but may change"; adopters
  who depend on specific shapes should pin. Post-B5 adoption feedback
  drives the 1.0.0 cut.

  Why unscoped `typed-nl` instead of scoped `@.../tnl` or the
  unscoped `tnl`: `tnl` itself on npm is taken (an unrelated ngrok
  tunnel tool from 2017). `typed-nl` as an unscoped name matches the
  project identity ("Typed Natural Language"), keeps install commands
  short (`npx typed-nl init`), and avoids the `@scope/name` indirection
  that forces `npx -p ... <bin>` verbosity when the unscoped package
  name doesn't match any declared bin. The `tnl` bin itself is the
  global command; it doesn't collide with the ngrok package unless
  both are installed globally at once.
